The '''Aichivirus A''' formerly '''Aichi virus''' ('''AiV''')<ref name=Carmona>Carmona-Vicente N ''et al'' (2013). Phylogeny and prevalence of kobuviruses in dogs and cats in the UK. ''Vet Microbiol'' [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23490561 Feb 26]</ref> is a small, round, [[cytopathic]] [[RNA virus#Single-stranded RNA viruses and RNA Sense|positive sense and ssRNA virus]]. Originally identified after a 1989 outbreak of acute [[gastroenteritis]] in the [[Aichi Prefecture]], probably linked to raw [[oyster]], genetic analysis has classified it as belonging to the family [[Picornaviridae]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Mahy|first=Brian W J|title=A dictionary of virology|date=2001|publisher=Academic Press|location=San Diego, Calif. [u.a.]|isbn=0-12-465327-8|pages=9|edition=3.}}</ref><ref name="Desselberger2003">{{cite book|author=U. Desselberger|title=Viral Gastroenteritis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=crOf-W3g-MQC&pg=PA645|year=2003|publisher=Gulf Professional Publishing|isbn=978-0-444-51444-8|pages=645–}}</ref> genus [[Kobuvirus]].<ref name=Carmona/>

It has since been isolated in studies of [[Finland|Finnish]] children,<ref>{{cite book|title=Issues in Global, Public, Community, and Institutional Health: 2011 Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Txe-WGjCm-oC&pg=PT793|date=9 January 2012|publisher=ScholarlyEditions|isbn=978-1-4649-6382-7|page=793}}</ref> [[Pakistani]] children, and [[Japan]]ese travelers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Yamashita|first1=Teruo|last2=Sakae|first2=Kenji|last3=Kobayashi|first3=Shinichi|last4=Ishihara|first4=Yuichi|last5=Miyake|first5=Takashi|last6=Mubina|first6=Agboatwalla|last7=Isomura|first7=Shin|title=Isolation of Cytopathic Small Round Virus (Aichi Virus) from Pakistani Children and Japanese Travelers from Southeast Asia|journal=Microbiology and Immunology|volume=39|issue=6|pages=433–435|doi=10.1111/j.1348-0421.1995.tb02225.x}}</ref>

