[[File:Antonio Longoria.png|thumb|300px]] '''Antonio Longoria''' (August 14, 1890 - December 31, 1970) was a scientist who claimed to have invented a [[death ray]] in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Inventor Hides Secret of Death Ray |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2CYDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA117&dq=popular+science+%22death+ray%22 |quote= |work=[[Popular Science]] |date=February 1, 1940 |accessdate=2008-12-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Gadgeteers Gather|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,787991-2,00.html |quote=[[Albert G. Burns]] of Oakland, Calif, was re-elected president of the Congress. It was Mr. Burns who last year revealed that a Clevelander named Antonio Longoria had invented a death-ray which killed rabbits, dogs & cats instantly. President Burns said that Inventor Longoria would withhold his secret until invasion threatened the U. S. |work=[[Time magazine]] |date=January 21, 1935 |accessdate=2008-12-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Too Specific |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,772264,00.html |quote=He is also a persistent and well-publicized ballyhooer of the 'death ray' machine he claims to have invented. Says he, this machine can kill cats and dogs, bring down pigeons on the wing, at ranges up to four miles. |work=[[Time magazine]] |date=October 23, 1939 |accessdate=2009-11-12 }}</ref>
==Biography== He was born in [[Madrid]], [[Spain]] on August 14, 1890.<ref>World War I draft registration</ref> He received his degree in engineering and a [[Ph.D.]] in medicine. In 1911 he emigrated to the [[United States]]. He moved to [[Cleveland, Ohio]] where he married and had three children. He became the president of the Sterling Electrical Company.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Welder at Work |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,762301,00.html |quote=Born in Madrid 46 years ago, Antonio Longoria attended Spanish schools, got a degree in engineering and a doctorate in medicine. In 1911 he arrived in the U. S., fonder of tinkering with machines than with people. Settling in Cleveland, he married, fathered three children, became president of Sterling Electrical Co.|work=[[Time magazine]] |date=August 10, 1936 |accessdate=2009-11-12 }}</ref> He became a naturalized US citizen on December 29, 1919.<ref>U.S. Naturalization Records Indexes, 1794-1995</ref> He claimed in 1936 that patents for his process for welding [[ferrous]] and [[nonferrous]] metals by his "invisible ray" were sold for $6,000,000.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Dr. Longoria, Inventor, Says Here U.S. Steel Was a Buyer of Invisible Ray Process. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/07/29/archives/welding-patents-sold-for-6000000-dr-longoria-inventor-says-here-us.html |quote=Patents for his newly invented process of welding ferrous and nonferrous metals by means of an invisible ray have yielded Dr. Antonio Longoria of Cleveland about $6,000,000, the inventor declared yesterday when he arrived in New York City. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 29, 1936 |accessdate=2009-11-12 }}</ref> He died on, New Year's Eve, December 31, 1970 in [[Winter Park, Florida]].<ref>[[Social Security Death Index]]</ref><ref>Florida Death Index, 1877-1998</ref>
