'''Epstein–Barr virus latent membrane protein 1 (LMP1)''' is an [[Epstein–Barr virus]] (EBV) protein that regulates its own expression and the expression of human genes.<ref name="pmid22318153">{{cite journal|last=Pratt|first=Z|author2=Zhang, J |author3=Sugden, B. |title=The latent membrane protein 1 (LMP1) oncogene of Epstein–Barr virus can simultaneously induce and inhibit apoptosis in B cells|journal=Journal of Virology|year=2012|volume=86|pages=4380–4393|pmid=22318153|doi=10.1128/JVI.06966-11|issue=8|pmc=3318665}}</ref>   LMP1 has a molecular weight of approximately 63 kDa,  and its expression induces many of the changes associated with EBV infections and activation of primary B cells.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gupta|title=Latent Membrane Protein 1 as a molecular adjuvant for single-cycle lentiviral vaccines|journal=Retrovirology| year=2011|volume=8| url=http://www.retrovirology.com/content/8/1/39|issue=1|doi=10.1186/1742-4690-8-39|pages=39|pmid=21592361|pmc=3118346}}</ref>  
LMP1 is the best-documented [[Oncogene|oncoprotein]] of the EBV latent gene products, as it is expressed in most EBV-related human cancers.<ref name="pmid23793113">{{cite journal|title=NF-κB and IRF7 pathway activation by Epstein-Barr virus Latent Membrane Protein 1|journal=Viruses|date= Jun 21, 2013|volume= 5|issue=6|edition=6|pages=1587–606| doi=10.3390/v5061587|pmid=23793113|pmc=3717723|last= Ersing|first= I|last2= Bernhardt |first2=K|last3= Gewurz|first3= BE}}</ref>

The structure of LMP1 consists of a short cytoplasmic [[N-terminus tail]], six [[Transmembrane domain|trans-membrane domains]], and a long cytoplasmic C-terminus, which contains three activating domains: CTARt, CTAR2, and CTAR3.  Each CTAR domain contains an amino acid sequence that serves as a recognition site for cellular adaptors to bind and trigger a series of signal transduction pathways that can lead to a change in gene expression.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Li|first=H|author2=Chang, Y|title=Epstein–barr virus latent membrane protein 1: Structure and functions|journal=J Biomed. Sci.|year=2003|volume=10|issue=5|pages=490–504|doi=10.1159/000072376|pmid=12928589}}</ref>

LMP-1 is a functional homologue of [[tumor necrosis factor]]<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=18057241|pmc=2258704|year=2008|author1=Cameron|first1=J. E.|title=Epstein-Barr virus latent membrane protein 1 induces cellular MicroRNA miR-146a, a modulator of lymphocyte signaling pathways|journal=Journal of Virology|volume=82|issue=4|pages=1946–58|last2=Yin|first2=Q|last3=Fewell|first3=C|last4=Lacey|first4=M|last5=McBride|first5=J|last6=Wang|first6=X|last7=Lin|first7=Z|last8=Schaefer|first8=B. C.|last9=Flemington|first9=E. K.|doi=10.1128/JVI.02136-07}}</ref> and mediates signaling through the [[nuclear factor-κB]] pathway, mimicking [[CD40]] receptor signaling.<ref name="pmid22318153"/><ref name="pmid23793113"/>

It is often found in [[Reed–Sternberg cell]]s.<ref name="pmid12796376">{{cite journal |vauthors=Herling M, Rassidakis GZ, Medeiros LJ |title=Expression of Epstein–Barr virus latent membrane protein-1 in Hodgkin and Reed-Sternberg cells of classical Hodgkin's lymphoma: associations with presenting features, serum interleukin 10 levels, and clinical outcome |journal=Clin. Cancer Res. |volume=9 |issue=6 |pages=2114–20 |date=June 2003 |pmid=12796376 |doi= |url=http://clincancerres.aacrjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=12796376|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref name="pmid16732997">{{cite journal |author=Andersson J |title=Epstein–Barr virus and Hodgkin's lymphoma |journal=Herpes |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=12–6 |date=May 2006 |pmid=16732997 |doi= |url=http://openurl.ingenta.com/content/nlm?genre=article&issn=0969-7667&volume=13&issue=1&spage=12&aulast=Andersson}}</ref>

