{{multiple issues| {{onesource|date=August 2015}} {{refimprove|date=August 2015}} }} {{Infobox galaxy | name = Abell 85-Brightest Cluster Galaxy | image = | caption = | epoch = [[Epoch (astronomy)#Julian years and J2000|J2000.0]] | pronounce = | constellation name = [[Cetus]] | ra = {{RA|00|41|50.5}} | dec = {{DEC|-09|18|11|}} | z = 0.055672 | h_radial_v = 16690&nbsp;km/s | gal_v = 16747&nbsp;km/s | dist_ly = {{convert|704|e6ly|Mpc|abbr=on|lk=on}}{{hub|0.678}} | group_cluster = [[Abell 85]] | type = cD;BrClG | mass = 7{{e|13}} | mass_light_ratio = | size = {{convert|270000|ly|kpc|lk=on|abbr=on}} | stars = 5{{e|12}} | appmag_v = 14.7 | appmag_b = | absmag_v = | size_v = 1.3 [[minute of arc|moa]] | notes = | names = Abell 85-BCG | references = }}
'''Holmberg 15A''' is a supergiant [[elliptical galaxy]] and the [[Type-cD galaxy|central dominant galaxy]] of the [[Abell 85]] [[galaxy cluster]] in the [[constellation]] [[Cetus]], about 700 million light-years from Earth. It was discovered c. 1937 by [[Erik Holmberg (astronomer)|Erik Holmberg]].<ref name=Cutie>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1088/2041-8205/795/2/L31 | title = The Brightest Cluster Galaxy in Abell 85: The Largest Core Known So Far | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 795 | issue = 2 | pages = L31 | year = 2014 | last1 = López-Cruz | first1 = O. | last2 = Añorve | first2 = C. | last3 = Birkinshaw | first3 = M. | last4 = Worrall | first4 = D. M. | last5 = Ibarra-Medel | first5 = H. J. | last6 = Barkhouse | first6 = W. A. | last7 = Torres-Papaqui | first7 = J. P. | last8 = Motta | first8 = V. | arxiv = 1405.7758 | bibcode = 2014ApJ...795L..31L }}</ref> It briefly shot to fame when it was reported to have the largest core ever observed in a galaxy, spanning some 15,000 light years<ref name=Cutie />, however this was subsequently refuted.<ref>Bonfini, Paolo; Dullo, Bililign T.; Graham, Alister W. (2015), [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2015ApJ...807..136B Too Big to Be Real? No Depleted Core in Holm 15A]</ref><ref>Madrid, Juan P.; Donzelli, Carlos J. (2016), [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016ApJ...819...50M The Abell 85 BCG: A Nucleated, Coreless Galaxy]</ref>
== Supermassive black hole ==
It has been alleged that the primary component of the galactic core is a [[supermassive black hole]] with a mass of 10 billion {{solar mass}}<ref name=Cutie />, although no direct measurement has yet been acquired. Previous estimates by Lauer ''et al'' have jointed a mass value as high as 310 billion {{solar mass}}<ref name=Cutie /> using the [[gamma ray point break radius method]]. Kormendy and Bender gave a value of 260 billion {{solar mass}} in a 2009 paper. Lower estimates were given by Kormendy and Ho ''et al'' in 2013 at 2.1 and 9.2 billion {{solar mass}}.<ref name=Cutie /> The paper by Lopez-Cruz ''et al''<ref name=Cutie /> stated: "Therefore, we conservatively suggest that Holm 15A hosts an SMBH with M• ∼ 1{{e|10}} M⊙". Kormendy and Ho ''et al'' derived these equations using the [[M-sigma relation]] and the size of the outer bulge of the galaxy, which are indirect estimates. Rusli ''et al'' derived a value of 170 billion {{solar mass}} using break radius methodology. In addition, Abell 85 has its velocity dispersion of dark matter halo at ~750&nbsp;km/s, which could only be explained by a black hole with a mass greater than 150 billion {{solar mass}}, although Kormendy and Ho ''et al'' stated that "dark matter halos are scale-free, and the SMBH-dark matter coevolution is independent from the effects of baryons".<ref name=Cutie /> This makes it one of the [[List of most massive black holes|most massive black holes]] ever discovered.
