{{math-competition-stub}}

{{short description|A coupled Earth system modeling package that integrates atmospheric, oceanographic and cryospheric modeling on a variety of scales}}
{{Multiple issues|{{advert|date=May 2015}}{{technical|date=May 2015}}
}}
The '''Model for Prediction Across Scales''' ('''MPAS''') is a coupled Earth system modeling package that integrates [[Atmospheric model|atmospheric]], oceanographic and cryospheric modeling on a variety of scales from the [[General Circulation Model|planetary]] to regional and mesoscale/microscale. It includes [[Climate model|climate]] and [[Numerical weather prediction|weather]] modeling and simulations that were first used by researchers in 2013.<ref>[https://nar.ucar.edu/2013/nesl/72b3-model-prediction-across-scales-mpas-0 2013 NESL Annual Report: The Model for Prediction Across Scales (MPAS)]</ref> The atmospheric components (MPAS-A) were led by the [[National Center for Atmospheric Research]] (NCAR)'s Earth System Laboratory (NESL) and the oceanographic components (MPAS-O) by the Climate, Ocean, and Sea Ice Modeling Group (COSIM) at [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] (LANL).<ref>[http://www.ncl.ucar.edu/Applications/mpas.shtml NCAR Command Language: MPAS]</ref> It has been used for real-time weather as well as seasonal forecasting of [[Atmospheric convection|convection]], [[tornado]]es<ref>[http://www2.ucar.edu/atmosnews/perspective/9996/long-range-tornado-prediction-it-feasible Long-range tornado prediction: Is it feasible?]</ref> and [[tropical cyclone]]s,<ref>[http://ncar.ucar.edu/budget-and-planning/2015-ncar-program-operating-plan/61112-hurricane-prediction 2015 NCAR Program Operating Plan: Hurricane Prediction]</ref> among other uses. Its atmospheric modeling aspects are intended to use<ref name="NCAR 2014">[http://ncar.ucar.edu/budget-and-planning/2014-ncar-program-operating-plan/5153-the-model-for-prediction-across-scales 2014 NCAR Program Operating Plan: The Model for Prediction Across Scales (MPAS)]</ref> and complement rather than replace the [[Weather Research and Forecasting Model]] (WRF-ARW/NMM), the [[Global Forecast System]] (GFS) and the [[Community Earth System Model]] (CESM).<ref>[https://mpas-dev.github.io/ MPAS Atmosphere]</ref>

