'''Natalia Dubrovinskaia''' (born 18 February 1961) is a Swedish [[geologist]] of [[Russians|Russian]] origin. In 2005, she led<ref> {{cite news |author=Knight W. |title=Nano-material is harder than diamonds |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn7926 |work=[[New Scientist]] |date=30 August 2005 |accessdate=2009-01-18 }}</ref> a team of researchers from the [[University of Bayreuth]] who were reported to have produced [[aggregated diamond nanorods]] from fullerene under high temperatures and pressures.<ref> {{cite news |author=Jeandron M. |title=Diamonds are not forever |url=http://physicsworld.com/cws/article/news/22997 |work=[[Physics World]] |date=26 August 2005 |accessdate=2009-01-18 }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal |author1=Dubrovinskaia N. |author2=Dubrovinsky L. |author3=Crichton W. |author4=Langenhorst F. |author5=Richter A. |title=Aggregated diamond nanorods, the densest and least compressible form of carbon |journal=[[Applied Physics Letters]] |volume=87 |issue=8 |page=083106 |doi=10.1063/1.2034101 |year=2005 |bibcode = 2005ApPhL..87h3106D }}</ref> Two years earlier large samples of nanodiamond were produced in a cheaper way (from graphite) and discovered to be harder than diamond by Japanese researchers.<ref> {{cite journal |author1=Irifune T. |author2=Kurio A. |author3=Sakamoto S. |author4=Inoue T. |author5=Sumiya H. |title=Materials: Ultrahard polycrystalline diamond from graphite |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |volume=421 |issue=6923 |pages=599–600 |year=2003 |doi=10.1038/421599b |pmid=12571587 |bibcode = 2003Natur.421..599I }}</ref> Dubrovinskaia currently works at the [[University of Heidelberg]] in [[Germany]] as a ''Privatdozent'' and Senior Scientist.
==Personal== Dubrovinskaia is married to Leonid Dubrovinsky, a geoscientist at University of Bayreuth [http://www.lightsources.org/leonid-dubrovinsky-geoscientist-university-bayreuth-germany-and-esrf-user?qt-sitewide_events=0].
